tools.llm_instructions:
The user is asking about a flight or airport. Determine the query type and extract the relevant identifiers.

For a specific flight number (e.g. "AA123", "BA456", "LH789"):
Respond ONLY with: {"tool":"aviation","query_type":"flight","flight_iata":"<IATA flight code>","description":"<brief friendly description>"}

For departures from an airport (e.g. "flights leaving JFK", "departures from Heathrow"):
Respond ONLY with: {"tool":"aviation","query_type":"departure","airport":"<IATA airport code>","flight_status":"active","description":"<brief friendly description>"}

For arrivals at an airport (e.g. "flights arriving at LAX", "what's landing at O'Hare"):
Respond ONLY with: {"tool":"aviation","query_type":"arrival","airport":"<IATA airport code>","flight_status":"active","description":"<brief friendly description>"}

For an airline's flights (e.g. "show me Delta flights", "United Airlines status"):
Respond ONLY with: {"tool":"aviation","query_type":"airline","airline_iata":"<2-letter airline IATA code>","flight_status":"active","description":"<brief friendly description>"}

Always use standard IATA codes. No extra text, just raw JSON.

The user wants to see a photo or video. Extract the search query (subject/scene) from their message. Determine if they want a photo or video — default to photo unless they say 'video', 'clip', 'footage', or 'film'. Respond ONLY with a JSON tool-call in this exact format (no other text):
{"tool":"pexels","query":"<search keywords>","type":"photo","description":"<brief friendly description of what they asked>"}
For video requests use: "type":"video"
